<p class="">    <h2>Key Challenges in the Ozone Generation Market</h2>    <ul>        <li>            <strong>Regulatory Compliance:</strong> The ozone generation market faces stringent regulations concerning the use and emission of ozone. Companies must navigate complex legal frameworks, which can hinder operational efficiency and increase compliance costs.        </li>        <li>            <strong>Market Perception:</strong> Ozone, while effective for disinfection and purification, carries a perception of being hazardous. This skepticism among consumers and businesses can limit market acceptance and adoption of ozone technology.        </li>        <li>            <strong>High Initial Investment:</strong> The capital expenditure for ozone generation systems can be substantial. This high initial cost can be a barrier for small to medium enterprises, preventing them from investing in advanced ozone solutions.        </li>        <li>            <strong>Technical Challenges:</strong> The production and deployment of ozone generators involve technical complexities, including optimization of output levels and management of by-products. Fluctuations in operational efficiency may affect overall performance.        </li>        <li>            <strong>Maintenance Requirements:</strong> Ozone generation systems necessitate regular maintenance to ensure optimal performance. This ongoing operational expense can be a concern for companies looking to minimize overhead costs.        </li>    </ul>        <h2>Potential Growth Opportunities in the Ozone Generation Market</h2>    <ul>        <li>            <strong>Emerging Applications:</strong> The rising demand for clean water and air presents opportunities for ozone technology in sectors such as municipal water treatment, wastewater management, and air purification. Ozone's effectiveness as a disinfectant can facilitate its adoption in these domains.        </li>        <li>            <strong>Technological Advancements:</st